</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Prime Locations</strong>: Barton Park, Carver, McIver State Park.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Ideal Baits</strong>: Beads, shrimp tails, and roe fished under a float.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    <strong>Essential Gear for Winter Steelhead Fishing</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Cold-weather fishing calls for tough gear and warm layers. Pack wisely:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod</strong>: 8.5- to 9.5-foot medium-heavy action rod.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Reel</strong>: Spinning or baitcasting, with smooth drag.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line</strong>: 10- to 15-pound test monofilament or braided line.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Clothing</strong>: Waterproof jacket, thermal base layers, neoprene waders.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>Recommended Tackle for Cold Water Fishing</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Hooks</strong>: Size 2 to 4.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Floats</strong>: Use drift floats or slip bobbers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Weights</strong>: Pencil lead or split shot to keep bait in strike zone.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    <strong>Best Baits and Lures for Winter Steelhead</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Steelhead can be picky in cold water, so bring a mix:
</p>
<ul>
